problems.problem:
In this problem we model a drag force due to electrostatic interactions. 
    \begin{anum}
        \item A particle of mass $m$ and positive charge $q$ is initially traveling at a speed $v$ in the positive $x$-direction. Its path intersects the $y$-axis at the point $y=b$. There exists a ball of mass $M\gg m$ and positive charge $Q$ initially at rest at the origin. For this part, assume $v$ is sufficiently large so that the particle is deflected by a small angle $\theta\ll 1$ after passing the ball. 
        \begin{enumerate}[label=(\roman*)]
        \item Find $\theta$ in terms of the other variables. 
        \item Find the momentum imparted to the ball in this interaction. 
        \end{enumerate}
        \item Now consider a ``gas" of particles of mass $m$ and charge $q$ at rest in space, with number density $n$. A ball of mass $M$ and charge $Q$ moves through this gas at speed $u$. Neglect the influence of (the small proportion) of charges that are deflected by a non-small angle amount, and assume the span of the ``gas" has a characteristic length $L$. Estimate the net drag force $F$ exerted on the ball as a function of $u$.
    \end{anum}
